{
  "format": "tiptap/v1",
  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "pgvector is a PostgreSQL extension that adds a native "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "vector"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " column type and approximate nearest-neighbour operators. By storing embeddings in the same database as your relational data, you can combine semantic similarity search with SQL filters in a single query — no round-trip to a separate vector store required. This document shows how to set up pgvector, generate and store embeddings, run hybrid queries, and use the results as grounded context for Claude."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "pgvector RAG architecture diagram: documents are chunked and sent to an embedding model (Cohere/OpenAI/sentence-transformers), stored in PostgreSQL with a vector(1536) column and IVFFlat/HNSW index. At query time, the user query is embedded, cosine search retrieves top-K chunks, and Claude uses those chunks plus the original query to generate a grounded answer."
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Installing pgvector"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "pgvector ships as a PostgreSQL extension. On most managed services (RDS, Supabase, Neon) it is available by default; on self-hosted Postgres, install the package first:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "bash"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# Debian/Ubuntu (PostgreSQL 16)\napt-get install postgresql-16-pgvector\n\n# macOS with Homebrew\nbrew install pgvector\n\n# Or build from source\ngit clone https://github.com/pgvector/pgvector.git\ncd pgvector && make && make install"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "sql"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "-- Enable the extension in your database (run once per database)\nCREATE EXTENSION IF NOT EXISTS vector;\n\n-- Confirm\nSELECT * FROM pg_extension WHERE extname = 'vector';"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Schema Design"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Add an embedding column to your existing table, or create a dedicated chunks table for document storage. The dimension must match the model output — 1536 for OpenAI text-embedding-3-small, 1024 for Cohere embed-v3, 768 for many sentence-transformers models."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "sql"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "-- Extend an existing table\nALTER TABLE documents ADD COLUMN embedding vector(1536);\n\n-- Or create a dedicated chunks table\nCREATE TABLE document_chunks (\n    id          BIGSERIAL PRIMARY KEY,\n    document_id BIGINT REFERENCES documents(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n    chunk_index INT    NOT NULL,\n    text        TEXT   NOT NULL,\n    token_count INT,\n    metadata    JSONB  DEFAULT '{}',\n    embedding   vector(1536)          -- NULL until populated\n);\n\n-- Composite index for fetching all chunks for a document\nCREATE INDEX idx_chunks_doc ON document_chunks (document_id, chunk_index);"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "metadata"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " JSONB column is the key to hybrid search: it stores the relational attributes (author, date, category, language, access tier) that you filter on before or after the vector search."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Generating and Storing Embeddings"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Because Anthropic does not expose a public embeddings API, use a third-party embedding service. Cohere and OpenAI are the most common choices for production; sentence-transformers (via Python) is the standard for on-premises or cost-sensitive workloads."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import cohere\nimport psycopg2\nimport psycopg2.extras\n\nco = cohere.Client(api_key=\"...\")\n\ndef embed_texts(texts: list[str]) -> list[list[float]]:\n    \"\"\"Cohere embed-v3 — 1024 dimensions.\"\"\"\n    resp = co.embed(\n        texts=texts,\n        model=\"embed-english-v3.0\",\n        input_type=\"search_document\",\n    )\n    return resp.embeddings\n\ndef store_chunks(conn, document_id: int, chunks: list[str]) -> None:\n    embeddings = embed_texts(chunks)\n    rows = [\n        (document_id, idx, text, emb)\n        for idx, (text, emb) in enumerate(zip(chunks, embeddings))\n    ]\n    with conn:\n        with conn.cursor() as cur:\n            psycopg2.extras.execute_values(\n                cur,\n                \"\"\"\n                INSERT INTO document_chunks (document_id, chunk_index, text, embedding)\n                VALUES %s\n                \"\"\",\n                # pgvector accepts Python lists as vector literals\n                [(doc_id, idx, text, str(emb)) for doc_id, idx, text, emb in rows],\n            )"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "bold"
                  }
                ],
                "text": "Batch embedding:"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": " Send up to 96 texts per Cohere request (2048 for OpenAI) to amortise HTTP overhead. For large document corpora, fan out batches in parallel using a thread pool, but respect rate limits. pgvector accepts Python lists directly as vector literals when using psycopg2 with the pgvector adapter, or you can pass a string formatted as "
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "code"
                  }
                ],
                "text": "'[0.1, 0.2, ...]'"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Using the pgvector psycopg2 adapter"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# pip install pgvector\nfrom pgvector.psycopg2 import register_vector\n\nconn = psycopg2.connect(\"postgresql://...\")\nregister_vector(conn)   # registers numpy array <-> vector codec\n\nimport numpy as np\n\ndef store_chunks_typed(conn, document_id: int, chunks: list[str]) -> None:\n    embeddings = embed_texts(chunks)  # list[list[float]]\n    with conn:\n        with conn.cursor() as cur:\n            for idx, (text, emb) in enumerate(zip(chunks, embeddings)):\n                cur.execute(\n                    \"\"\"\n                    INSERT INTO document_chunks\n                        (document_id, chunk_index, text, embedding)\n                    VALUES (%s, %s, %s, %s)\n                    \"\"\",\n                    (document_id, idx, text, np.array(emb)),\n                )"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Index Types: IVFFlat vs HNSW"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Without an index, pgvector performs exact nearest-neighbour search using a sequential scan — accurate but O(n) per query. Both index types trade a small amount of recall for dramatically faster approximate search."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "sql"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "-- IVFFlat: partition vectors into lists, probe a subset at query time\n-- Build AFTER loading data (can't insert into partial IVFFlat index well)\n-- lists = sqrt(row count) is the standard starting point\nCREATE INDEX idx_chunks_ivf\n    ON document_chunks\n    USING ivfflat (embedding vector_cosine_ops)\n    WITH (lists = 100);\n\n-- At query time, increase probed lists for higher recall at the cost of speed:\nSET ivfflat.probes = 10;   -- default 1; try 10-20 for production\n\n-- HNSW: hierarchical navigable small world graph\n-- Builds at insert time; better recall than IVFFlat for the same query cost\nCREATE INDEX idx_chunks_hnsw\n    ON document_chunks\n    USING hnsw (embedding vector_cosine_ops)\n    WITH (m = 16, ef_construction = 64);\n\n-- ef_search controls query time/recall tradeoff:\nSET hnsw.ef_search = 40;   -- default 40; increase for better recall"
          }
        ]
      },
